definition.value: A univalent group formed by removing a hydrogen atom from any ring atom of a heterocyclic compound.
An S-alkylsulfenic acid in which the alkyl group is specified as methyl.
Drugs that bind to but do not activate serotonin receptors, thereby blocking the actions of serotonin or serotonergic agonists.

A L-histidine derivative that is N(alpha),N(alpha),N(alpha)-trimethyl-L-histidine in which the hydrogen at position 2 on the imdazole ring is replaced by a mercapto group. A naturally occurring metabolite of histidine synthesized by bacteria and fungi with antioxidant properties. It is found ubiquitously in plants and animals and is present in many human foodstuffs.
A member of the class of tryptamines that is serotonin in which one of the hydrogens attached to the primary amino group is replaced by a methyl group.
A tetritol that is butane substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 1, 2, 3 and 4.
An organobromine compound that is fluoranthene in which the hydrogens at positions 7 and 10 are substituted by 4-bromophenyl groups, while those at positions 8 and 9 are substituted by phenyl groups.

An organobromine compound that is fluoranthene in which the hydrogens at positions 7 and 10 are substituted by 4-bromophenyl groups, while those at positions 8 and 9 are substituted by 4-octylphenyl groups.

An organobromine compound that is fluoranthene in which the hydrogens at positions 7 and 10 are substituted by 4-bromophenyl groups, while those at positions 8 and 9 are substituted by nonyl and octyl groups, respectively.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of 2-aminobut-2-enoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An apiitol that has R-configuration at the chiral centre.
A monovalent inorganic anion that consists of triphosphoric acid in which one of the five OH groups has been deprotonated.
A divalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of two protons from triphosphoric acid.
A trivalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of three protons from triphosphoric acid.
